Find the ordered pair $(x,y)$ if

\begin{align*}
x+y&=(5-x)+(5-y),\\
x-y&=(x-1)+(y-1).
\end{align*}

inference:
**Solution:**

\begin{align*}
x+y&=(5-x)+(5-y),\\
\Rightarrow\qquad 2x+2y&=10,\\
\Rightarrow\qquad x+y&=5\tag 1.
\end{align*}

\begin{align*}
x-y&=(x-1)+(y-1),\\
\Rightarrow\qquad x-y&=x-1+y-1,\\
\Rightarrow\qquad x-y&=x+y-2,\\
\Rightarrow\qquad y&=-1\tag 2.
\end{align*}

Substituting $(2)$ into $(1)$, we get

\begin{align*}
x+(-1)&=5,\\
\Rightarrow\qquad x&=6.
\end{align*}

Therefore, the ordered pair is $(x,y)=(6,-1)$.

**Final Answer: $\boxed{(6,-1)}$. I hope it is correct.**

